Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp}. When boiling, add the @linguine{180%g} to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

While the pasta cooks, peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}). Drain the @king prawns{300%g}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the @diced chorizo{60%g} and fry until it starts to brown, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Next, add the prawns and stir-fry for ~{2-3%minutes}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. Stir in the garlic and fry for ~{30%seconds}.

Stir the @chicken stock paste{10%g}, @creme fraiche{150%g} and @water{75%ml} for the sauce into the pan. Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, once the pasta is cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pan. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Once the sauce has thickened, stir in the @peas{120%g} and the @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%g}. Cook until the peas are piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Stir in the cooked pasta. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Share the creamy chorizo and prawn linguine between your #bowls{}. Top with a handful of @wild rocket{20%g} and drizzle over the @balsamic glaze{12%ml} to finish. Enjoy!